values.comments:
This course is a general laboratory course covering aspects of qualitative and quantitative analysis, determination of chemical and physical properties, and chemical synthesis. Chemistry 101 is the co-requisite; if a student withdraws from or drops from a co-requisite course, he/she must also withdraw from or drop the laboratory course. There is a $150 lab fee for CHEM-053. &#8232;

Students found the course content to be as expected for an introductory laboratory course. The material and concepts were easy to understand and follow. &#8232;&#8232;&#8232;

Professor Philips was touted as “one of [the] best teachers” in the Chemistry department, both “very nice and compassionate” as well as “funny.” Students found her to be thorough and “very concerned with the students’ understanding of each concept she presented.” &#8232;&#8232;&#8232;

The workload for this course was described as being very easy and not at all unreasonable; students found the course content straightforward and fairly simple. CHEM-101, the co-requisite course, fulfills the physical world sector and is suitable for both majors and non-majors with high school chemistry and calculus. Students with at least a high school chemistry and calculus background should be prepared for this course; otherwise, lower level Chemistry classes are recommended.
